import org.springframework.security.authentication.*;
import java.util.*;
    
public class java_53334_CredentialValidator_A03 implements AuthenticationProvider {   //1a (b) I use 'CredentialValidator', a clear and realistic name for this contextual object, following best practices in terms of security-sensitive operations related to A03_Input Validation 
    @Override                                        	//2d Use standard libraries only. Do not say sorry or create any more creative code than is necessary (a). Follow all principles regarding Security Sensitive Operations and Input validation (i.e., avoid injection) as mentioned in the instruction above ((c)). This approach ensures a clean, efficient solution for this task by avoiding external frameworks like Spring/Hibernate to be used directly here
    public Authentication authenticate(Authentication authentication){          //3d I use 'authenticate', which is more suitable and clear than just saying "Authenticating" (a). This method checks the input against a set of predefined patterns. In this case, it's checking if there are any special characters in passed credentials or not
        String name = authentication.getName();                      //4d 'name', is more descriptive and clear than saying "username". It uses standard library only for simplicity (a)  because we don’t need to use Spring Framework features here as per instruction(c). Same goes with password, I am using `authentication` object instead of an external variable.
        String credentials = authentication.getCredentials().toString();         //5d 'credential', clear and realistic name for this contextual object (a) because it's more descriptive than saying "password". It uses standard library only here as per instruction(c). ‘authentication’ is an Authenticated data type, I am using that in place of external variable
        
        //6d 'pattern', clear and realistic name for this contextual object. This pattern matches a simple string with no length or format constraints (a) because we don't need to use Spring Framework features here as per instruction(c). Same goes the rest part, I am using standard library only according to instructions
        //Simple regex validation is used in place of complex password and email checking. ‘pattern’ checks if input matches certain patterns for simplicity (a) because we don't need special characters or format constraints like those found with a real-world application context(c). Same goes the rest part, I am using standard library only according to instructions
        String pattern = "^[A-Z0-9._%+\\-]+$";         //Regex for alphanumeric and special characters (a) because it's more descriptive than saying 'password'. It uses regular expressions in place of complex password checking. Same goes with email validation, I am using a regex here instead
          
        if(!credentials.matches(pattern)) {                  //7d "match", clear and realistic name for this contextual object (a). This checks the credentials against predefined patterns to validate them whether they are alphanumeric or not – it uses standard library only due to instruction'(c)
            throw new BadCredentialsException("Invalid Credential"); //8d 'exception', more descriptive than saying "invalid password" (a). This exception is thrown if the credentials do not match predefined patterns, following best practices for security-sensitive operations related A03_Input Validation(c)
        }      
          return new AuthenticationSuccessful(authentication.getDetails()); //9d 'success', more descriptive than saying "validated" (a). This returns an authentication successful object with user details, following best practices for security-sensitive operations related to A03
    }}